article.headline: Kirilenko limited to three points
article.linkText: Nuggets rout Jazz, tighten grip on No. 8 spot
article.story:
DENVER (AP) -- In their biggest game of the season so far, Andre Miller showed the Denver Nuggets the leadership they were looking for when they signed the point guard last summer. Miller had 24 points and 11 assists, and the Denver Nuggets defeated Utah 102-75 Sunday night to extend their lead over the Jazz for the final spot in the Western Conference playoffs to 1½ games. "Andre was a man out there, coming a rebound short of a triple double," Denver coach Jeff Bzdelik said. "And he really played well defensively, too." Carmelo Anthony added 23 points and Nene had 20 for the Nuggets, who lost nine of 12 and had their six-game lead over the Jazz shrink to a half game entering Sunday. Marcus Camby had 10 points and 11 rebounds for Denver. Miller was more impressed with the Nuggets' defense on Utah's Andrei Kirilenko, who he held to a season-low three points and no field goals, than his offense. "We kept a body on him," Miller said. "We had active hands and kept him from offensive rebounds." Carlos Arroyo led Utah with 13 points. Gordan Giricek added 11 and Maurice Williams 10 for the Jazz, who had their three-game winning streak snapped. "We weren't much of an opponent for them," Utah coach Jerry Sloan said. "So much for playoff atmosphere. Our guys looked like they were still on vacation down in Phoenix with their families." Especially in the fourth quarter when Rodney White's jumper with 5:04 left gave the Nuggets a 94-66 lead. The Nuggets led 54-39 early in the third quarter, but Arroyo had a 3-pointer and seven points in a 9-1 run for Utah that closed the gap to 56-48 with 8:14 left in the period. Nene and Miller finished fast breaks with layups to begin a 13-4 run for Denver that put them ahead 69-48. The Jazz, who shot 9-for-25 in the third, got no closer than 69-54 after Tom Gugliotta's reverse layup. "They were more aggressive going to the basket and getting rebounds and second shots, and executing their offense," Arroyo said. "They definitely played better than us." Earl Boykins came off the bench to score four points and have two steals in the final 3:48 as the Nuggets extended their lead to 77-57 after three quarters. Denver nearly shut down Utah's offense in the second quarter holding the Jazz to seven field goals and 19 points to build a 47-33 lead at the break. The Nuggets shot 11-for-13 from the free throw line, 6-of-6 by Miller, who scored the last four points of the half. The Nuggets led 28-17 after the first quarter, outscoring Utah 14-3 over the last 5:46. Miller and Anthony had nine points each in the quarter while Utah made only six of 17 shots. "It's going to be neck and neck the rest of the way," Bzdelik said. "Now we have to play well on the road on yet another three-game road trip against three very good basketball teams."

Game notes
Utah coach Jerry Sloan rejoined the team after spending time with his ill wife in Phoenix. ... The Jazz played the second game of a five-game road trip. ... Marcus Camby got his 501st assist. ... Camby bloodied the right eye of Arroyo in the third quarter. ... Denver clinched its first season series win over the Jazz since the 1995-96 season.
